Although predominantly makes cone galls on leaves (Fig. 52
S-V
), two immatures were dissected from stem galls and one from a flower bud gall that DNA barcoded to this species, suggesting that some lability in galling exists (see Discussion). The cone gall extends from the lower surface of the leaf and the galls typically open on the upper leaf surface by a suture around the margin of the gall resembling a hinged trap door (Fig. 52W, X). The shape of the cone gall can vary depending on the host morphotype, galls on pubescent types tend to be broad and short (Fig. 52
U-V
), while those on glabrous types tend to be more narrow and elongate (Fig. 52
S-T
), in both cases gall tissue often becomes reddish in colour. Galls can be scattered across the leaf surface (Fig. 52
X-Y
) or clustered (Fig. 52V), and in some cases are found clustered linearly along the leaf midrib (Fig. 52S).
